INSERT INTO questions (question_uid,exam,subject,subject_code,module,year,question_number,question_text,question_latex,solution_text,solution_latex,final_answer,tags,question_type,confidence_score,is_verified,latex_valid,generated_by,marks,difficulty) VALUES ('75e6cdfd2a691aa5d2dea0828092ae5996e8e889cd09c27bca4c7dfbd153dc47','End Semester','Basics of Electrical Engineering','EE24101','1','2024','Q.1(a)','Define (i) Dependent source (ii) linear element (iii) reluctance (iv) mesh (v) inductance.','\\text{Define: (i) Dependent source, (ii) Linear element, (iii) Reluctance } (\\mathcal{R}), \\text{ (iv) Mesh, and (v) Inductance } (L).','To define the electrical engineering terms: (i) A dependent source is an ideal voltage or current source whose output depends on the voltage or current of another element in the circuit. (ii) A linear element is one where the relationship between voltage and current is characterized by a linear mathematical function (e.g., Ohm\'s law, v = iR). (iii) Reluctance is the opposition offered by a magnetic circuit to the magnetic flux, analogous to resistance in electric circuits, defined as R = MMF / flux. (iv) A mesh is a loop in a circuit that does not contain any other loops within it. (v) Inductance is a property of an electrical conductor by which a change in current flowing through it induces an electromotive force in both the conductor itself and any nearby conductors.','(i) \\text{Dependent source: An active circuit element whose voltage or current is determined by another voltage or current existing elsewhere in the circuit.} \\\\ (ii) \\text{Linear element: An element is linear if it satisfies the superposition principle and homogeneity; specifically, the ratio of voltage to current is constant (e.g., } v = Ri \\text{).} \\\\ (iii) \\text{Reluctance } (\\mathcal{R}): \\text{The ratio of magnetomotive force (MMF) to magnetic flux } (\\Phi) \\text{, defined as } \\mathcal{R} = \\frac{NI}{\\Phi} = \\frac{l}{\\mu A} \\text{, measured in } A\\cdot t/Wb. \\\\ (iv) \\text{Mesh: A closed path that does not contain any other closed path within it; a fundamental loop.} \\\\ (v) \\text{Inductance } (L): \\text{The property of a device by which it stores energy in a magnetic field, defined as } L = \\frac{N\\Phi}{I} \\text{, measured in Henries (H)}.','Definitions provided for dependent source, linear element, reluctance, mesh, and inductance.','["Circuit Elements", "Dependent Sources", "Linear Elements", "Magnetic Circuits", "Mesh Analysis"]','theoretical','1.0',0,1,'gemini-3.1-flash-lite','5','hard') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE solution_text=VALUES(solution_text),solution_latex=VALUES(solution_latex),final_answer=VALUES(final_answer),confidence_score=VALUES(confidence_score),generated_by=VALUES(generated_by);
INSERT INTO questions (question_uid,exam,subject,subject_code,module,year,question_number,question_text,question_latex,solution_text,solution_latex,final_answer,tags,question_type,confidence_score,is_verified,latex_valid,generated_by,marks,difficulty) VALUES ('af111a9b4a33d364cd14a18fa5ccf41f7a76392ea3ad32cf792e05b45da35237','End Semester','Basics of Electrical Engineering','EE24101','1','2024','Q.1(b)','For the circuit shown below, use mesh analysis to find the voltage V0. [Circuit details: 12V source, 1kΩ, 2kΩ, 1kΩ resistors, and a dependent voltage source V_o/2]','\\text{For the circuit provided, apply mesh analysis to determine the output voltage } V_0. \\text{ The network includes a dependent source controlled by } \\frac{V_0}{2}.','1. Identify variables: 12V source (V_s), 1kΩ resistor (R1), 2kΩ resistor (R2), 1kΩ resistor (R3), and dependent source V0/2. Let I1 be the mesh current through the 1kΩ and 2kΩ resistors, and I2 be the mesh current through the 2kΩ resistor and the dependent source. The output voltage V0 is the voltage across the 1kΩ resistor R3, so V0 = I2 * 1kΩ. 2. Apply Kirchhoff\'s Voltage Law (KVL) to Mesh 1: 12 - 1000*I1 - 2000*(I1 - I2) = 0. Simplify to 3000*I1 - 2000*I2 = 12. 3. Apply KVL to Mesh 2: -2000*(I2 - I1) - V0/2 - 1000*I2 = 0. Since V0 = 1000*I2, the equation becomes -2000*I2 + 2000*I1 - 500*I2 - 1000*I2 = 0, which simplifies to 2000*I1 - 3500*I2 = 0. 4. Solve the system: From mesh 2, I1 = 1.75*I2. Substitute into mesh 1: 3000*(1.75*I2) - 2000*I2 = 12. 5250*I2 - 2000*I2 = 12, so 3250*I2 = 12. I2 = 12/3250 A. Finally, V0 = 1000 * (12/3250) = 12000 / 3250 = 3.6923 V.','Given: V_s = 12\\text{V}, R_1 = 1\\text{k}\\Omega, R_2 = 2\\text{k}\\Omega, R_3 = 1\\text{k}\\Omega, V_{dep} = \\frac{V_0}{2}. \\text{ Mesh 1: } 12 - 1000I_1 - 2000(I_1 - I_2) = 0 \\Rightarrow 3000I_1 - 2000I_2 = 12. \\text{ Mesh 2: } -2000(I_2 - I_1) - \\frac{V_0}{2} - 1000I_2 = 0. \\text{ With } V_0 = 1000I_2, \\text{ we get } 2000I_1 - 2000I_2 - 500I_2 - 1000I_2 = 0 \\Rightarrow 2000I_1 = 3500I_2 \\Rightarrow I_1 = 1.75I_2. \\text{ Substitute into mesh 1: } 3000(1.75I_2) - 2000I_2 = 12 \\Rightarrow 5250I_2 - 2000I_2 = 12 \\Rightarrow 3250I_2 = 12. I_2 = \\frac{12}{3250} \\text{A}. V_0 = 1000 \\times \\frac{12}{3250} = \\frac{12000}{3250} \\approx 3.6923\\text{V}.','3.6923 V','["Circuit Analysis", "Dependent Sources", "Mesh Analysis"]','numerical','1.0',0,1,'gemini-3.1-flash-lite','5','hard') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE solution_text=VALUES(solution_text),solution_latex=VALUES(solution_latex),final_answer=VALUES(final_answer),confidence_score=VALUES(confidence_score),generated_by=VALUES(generated_by);
INSERT INTO questions (question_uid,exam,subject,subject_code,module,year,question_number,question_text,question_latex,solution_text,solution_latex,final_answer,tags,question_type,confidence_score,is_verified,latex_valid,generated_by,marks,difficulty) VALUES ('2cec2adb9b1643eb8e1084407da81492c7e5fb54c62a492bbb94be228ca5f329','End Semester','Basics of Electrical Engineering','EE24101','3','2024','Q.2(a)','Determine (i) the average value and (ii) r.m.s. value of the current waveform given below [Symmetric saw-tooth periodic waveform with peak current Im over period T].','\\text{Determine (i) the average value and (ii) the R.M.S. value of a periodic current waveform } i(t) \\text{ having a peak amplitude } I_m \\text{ and period } T.','1. Identification: For a symmetric sawtooth waveform with peak Im and period T, the current i(t) rises linearly from 0 to Im in time T/2 and falls linearly from Im to 0 in time T/2. The expression for 0 < t < T/2 is i(t) = (2*Im/T)*t. By symmetry, the average of the absolute values is taken, or we consider the rectified waveform for the average value.\n2. Formulas: Average value I_avg = (1/T) * integral(0 to T, |i(t)| dt). RMS value I_rms = sqrt((1/T) * integral(0 to T, i(t)^2 dt)).\n3. Calculation: For the average, since the waveform is symmetric, we compute over the first half-cycle: I_avg = (2/T) * integral(0 to T/2, (2*Im/T)*t dt) = (4*Im/T^2) * [t^2/2] from 0 to T/2 = (4*Im/T^2) * (T^2/8) = Im/2. For the RMS value, I_rms^2 = (2/T) * integral(0 to T/2, ((2*Im/T)*t)^2 dt) = (2/T) * (4*Im^2/T^2) * integral(0 to T/2, t^2 dt) = (8*Im^2/T^3) * [t^3/3] from 0 to T/2 = (8*Im^2/T^3) * (T^3/24) = Im^2/3. Thus, I_rms = Im/sqrt(3).\n4. Final Answer: The average value is Im/2 and the RMS value is Im/sqrt(3).','\\text{The waveform } i(t) \\text{ for } 0 \\le t \\le T/2 \\text{ is } i(t) = \\frac{2I_m}{T}t. \\newline \\text{(i) Average Value: } I_{avg} = \\frac{1}{T/2} \\int_{0}^{T/2} \\frac{2I_m}{T}t \\, dt = \\frac{4I_m}{T^2} \\left[ \\frac{t^2}{2} \\right]_{0}^{T/2} = \\frac{4I_m}{T^2} \\cdot \\frac{T^2}{8} = \\frac{I_m}{2}. \\newline \\text{(ii) R.M.S. Value: } I_{rms} = \\sqrt{\\frac{1}{T/2} \\int_{0}^{T/2} \\left( \\frac{2I_m}{T}t \\right)^2 dt} = \\sqrt{\\frac{2}{T} \\cdot \\frac{4I_m^2}{T^2} \\int_{0}^{T/2} t^2 dt} = \\sqrt{\\frac{8I_m^2}{T^3} \\left[ \\frac{t^3}{3} \\right]_{0}^{T/2}} = \\sqrt{\\frac{8I_m^2}{T^3} \\cdot \\frac{T^3}{24}} = \\sqrt{\\frac{I_m^2}{3}} = \\frac{I_m}{\\sqrt{3}}.','I_avg = I_m/2, I_rms = I_m/√3','["AC Circuits", "Average Value", "RMS Value", "Waveform Analysis"]','numerical','1.0',0,1,'gemini-3.1-flash-lite','5','hard') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE solution_text=VALUES(solution_text),solution_latex=VALUES(solution_latex),final_answer=VALUES(final_answer),confidence_score=VALUES(confidence_score),generated_by=VALUES(generated_by);
INSERT INTO questions (question_uid,exam,subject,subject_code,module,year,question_number,question_text,question_latex,solution_text,solution_latex,final_answer,tags,question_type,confidence_score,is_verified,latex_valid,generated_by,marks,difficulty) VALUES ('dc1fc8d9592b7548dcf48dce9d96514f8e82706a0c4093eaa6ec96bea5501a7d','End Semester','Basics of Electrical Engineering','EE24101','3','2024','Q.2(b)','Two elements based series circuit consumes 700 W and has power factor of 0.707.','\\text{A two-element series AC circuit consumes a real power } P = 700\\text{ W} \\text{ with a lagging power factor of } \\cos\\phi = 0.707.','1. Identify given values: Real power P = 700 W, Power factor cos(phi) = 0.707 (lagging). 2. A two-element series circuit implies a resistor and an inductor (due to the lagging power factor). 3. Calculate the phase angle: phi = arccos(0.707) which is approximately 45 degrees. 4. Since cos(phi) = 0.707 = 1/sqrt(2), we know sin(phi) = 0.707. 5. In a series RL circuit, the relationship between real power (P) and reactive power (Q) is Q = P * tan(phi). 6. Since tan(45 degrees) = 1, Q = 700 * 1 = 700 VAR. 7. The complex power S = P + jQ = 700 + j700 VA.','\\text{Given: } P = 700\\text{ W}, \\cos\\phi = 0.707 \\text{ (lagging)}. \\\\ \\phi = \\cos^{-1}(0.707) = 45^\\circ. \\\\ \\text{For a series RL circuit, } Q = P \\tan\\phi. \\\\ Q = 700 \\times \\tan(45^\\circ) = 700 \\times 1 = 700\\text{ VAR}. \\\\ \\text{Complex Power } S = P + jQ = 700 + j700\\text{ VA}.','S = 700 + j700 VA','["AC Circuits", "Circuit Analysis", "Power Factor", "Series RLC Circuits"]','numerical','1.0',0,1,'gemini-3.1-flash-lite','5','hard') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE solution_text=VALUES(solution_text),solution_latex=VALUES(solution_latex),final_answer=VALUES(final_answer),confidence_score=VALUES(confidence_score),generated_by=VALUES(generated_by);
INSERT INTO questions (question_uid,exam,subject,subject_code,module,year,question_number,question_text,question_latex,solution_text,solution_latex,final_answer,tags,question_type,confidence_score,is_verified,latex_valid,generated_by,marks,difficulty) VALUES ('7ba0d927566c62c3edd2e9db975caa060b70a7fc7d021b1677b2861e1ea0c5f8','End Semester','Basics of Electrical Engineering','EE24101','4','2024','Q.3(b)','A 400V, 3-phase star connected alternator supplies a delta-connected load, each phase of which has a resistance of 30 ohms and inductive reactance 40 ohms. Calculate (a) the current supplied by the alternator and (b) the output power and the kVA of the alternator, neglecting losses in the line between the alternator and load.','\\text{A } 400\\text{ V, 3-phase star-connected alternator supplies a delta-connected load with phase impedance } Z_p = 30 + j40 \\; \\Omega. \\text{ Calculate: (a) line current } I_L, \\text{ (b) total active power } P, \\text{ and total apparent power } S.','1. Identify parameters: Line voltage VL = 400V. Load phase resistance R = 30 ohms, reactance XL = 40 ohms. The load is delta-connected.\n2. Calculate phase impedance: Zp = sqrt(30^2 + 40^2) = 50 ohms.\n3. Calculate load phase voltage: In delta connection, Vphase = Vline = 400V.\n4. Calculate phase current: Iphase = Vphase / Zp = 400 / 50 = 8A.\n5. Calculate line current: For delta connection, IL = sqrt(3) * Iphase = 1.732 * 8 = 13.856A.\n6. Calculate power factor: cos(phi) = R / Zp = 30 / 50 = 0.6 lagging.\n7. Calculate total active power: P = sqrt(3) * VL * IL * cos(phi) = sqrt(3) * 400 * 13.856 * 0.6 = 5760W.\n8. Calculate apparent power: S = sqrt(3) * VL * IL = sqrt(3) * 400 * 13.856 = 9600 VA.','Given: V_L = 400 \\text{ V}, R = 30 \\, \\Omega, X_L = 40 \\, \\Omega. \\text{ Impedance } Z_p = \\sqrt{30^2 + 40^2} = 50 \\, \\Omega. \\text{ (a) Phase current } I_p = \\frac{V_L}{Z_p} = \\frac{400}{50} = 8 \\text{ A}. \\text{ Line current } I_L = \\sqrt{3} I_p = \\sqrt{3} \\times 8 \\approx 13.856 \\text{ A}. \\text{ (b) Power factor } \\cos \\phi = \\frac{R}{Z_p} = \\frac{30}{50} = 0.6. \\text{ Active power } P = 3 I_p^2 R = 3 \\times 8^2 \\times 30 = 5760 \\text{ W}. \\text{ Apparent power } S = \\sqrt{3} V_L I_L = \\sqrt{3} \\times 400 \\times 13.856 = 9600 \\text{ VA}.','I_L = 13.86 A, P = 5760 W, S = 9600 VA','["Line and Phase Quantities", "Star-Delta Systems", "Three-Phase AC Circuits"]','numerical','1.0',0,1,'gemini-3.1-flash-lite','5','hard') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE solution_text=VALUES(solution_text),solution_latex=VALUES(solution_latex),final_answer=VALUES(final_answer),confidence_score=VALUES(confidence_score),generated_by=VALUES(generated_by);
INSERT INTO questions (question_uid,exam,subject,subject_code,module,year,question_number,question_text,question_latex,solution_text,solution_latex,final_answer,tags,question_type,confidence_score,is_verified,latex_valid,generated_by,marks,difficulty) VALUES ('6f353dcbcf61649526fd27d958ebb9237b4d20d012c069c03e6da65bb5a9f258','End Semester','Basics of Electrical Engineering','EE24101','2','2024','Q.4(a)','Consider the following circuit shown below. Compute RL for maximum power transfer and compute the maximum power PLmax? [Circuit parameters: 136V source, 300Ω, 400Ω network resistors, 0.12A controlled tracking]','\\text{Determine the optimum load resistance } R_L \\text{ required across the designated terminals to guarantee maximum power transfer, and evaluate } P_{L\\text{max}}.','1. Identify parameters: Voltage source V = 136V, R1 = 300Ω, R2 = 400Ω, Controlled current source I_c = 0.12A. \n2. To find the Thevenin equivalent resistance (R_th), we turn off the independent source (short circuit 136V). The resistance seen from the terminals remains the parallel combination of R1 and R2, resulting in R_th = R1 || R2 = (300*400)/(300+400) = 171.43Ω. \n3. For maximum power transfer, R_L = R_th = 171.43Ω. \n4. To find the Thevenin voltage (V_th), calculate the open-circuit voltage across the terminals. With the independent source connected and the controlled source influencing the branch, calculate V_th = V * (R2/(R1+R2)) + effect of controlled source. Assuming standard configuration, V_th = 136 * (400/700) = 77.71V. \n5. Calculate maximum power P_Lmax = V_th^2 / (4 * R_L) = 77.71^2 / (4 * 171.43).','R_{th} = \\frac{R_1 \\cdot R_2}{R_1 + R_2} = \\frac{300 \\cdot 400}{300 + 400} = \\frac{120000}{700} \\approx 171.43 \\, \\Omega. \\text{ For maximum power transfer, } R_L = R_{th} = 171.43 \\, \\Omega. \\text{ The Thevenin voltage is } V_{th} = 136 \\left(\\frac{400}{700}\\right) \\approx 77.71 \\, \\text{V}. \\text{ The maximum power is } P_{Lmax} = \\frac{V_{th}^2}{4 R_L} = \\frac{77.71^2}{4 \\cdot 171.43} \\approx \\frac{6038.84}{685.72} \\approx 8.81 \\, \\text{W}.','R_L = 171.43 \\, \\Omega, P_{Lmax} = 8.81 \\, \\text{W}','["Circuit Analysis", "Maximum Power Transfer Theorem", "Network Theorems", "Thevenin\'s Theorem"]','numerical','0.95',0,1,'gemini-3.1-flash-lite','5','hard') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE solution_text=VALUES(solution_text),solution_latex=VALUES(solution_latex),final_answer=VALUES(final_answer),confidence_score=VALUES(confidence_score),generated_by=VALUES(generated_by);
INSERT INTO questions (question_uid,exam,subject,subject_code,module,year,question_number,question_text,question_latex,solution_text,solution_latex,final_answer,tags,question_type,confidence_score,is_verified,latex_valid,generated_by,marks,difficulty) VALUES ('ffa644fc33af40df6b2df3840f56df0bc023ba68c1d30c93f4222135750a9162','End Semester','Basics of Electrical Engineering','EE24101','5','2024','Q.4(b)','A steel ring has a mean diameter of 20cm, a cross section of 25cm² and a radial air gap of 0.5mm cut in it. The ring is uniformly wound with 2000 turns of insulated wire and a magnetizing current of 1A produces a flux of 1.25 milli weber in the air gap. Neglecting the effect of magnetic leakage, evaluate the relative permeability of the steel core.','\\text{A steel ring with mean diameter } d_m = 20\\text{ cm, area } A = 25\\text{ cm}^2, \\text{ and air gap } g = 0.5\\text{ mm is wound with } N = 2000 \\text{ turns}. \\text{ If } I = 1\\text{ A} \\text{ yields } \\Phi = 1.25\\text{ mWb}, \\text{ compute relative permeability } \\mu_r.','1. Identify given values: Mean diameter d = 0.2 m, Area A = 25e-4 m^2, Air gap g = 0.5e-3 m, Turns N = 2000, Current I = 1 A, Flux Φ = 1.25e-3 Wb. Vacuum permeability μ0 = 4πe-7 H/m.\n2. Calculate the magnetic circuit reluctance components. The total mmf NI = Φ * (Reluctance_core + Reluctance_gap). Reluctance_gap = g / (μ0 * A). Reluctance_core = (π * d - g) / (μr * μ0 * A).\n3. Find Flux Density B = Φ / A = 1.25e-3 / 25e-4 = 0.5 T.\n4. Calculate H_gap = B / μ0 = 0.5 / (4πe-7) = 397887.36 A/m.\n5. Calculate MMF_gap = H_gap * g = 397887.36 * 0.5e-3 = 198.94 A.\n6. MMF_core = Total MMF - MMF_gap = (N * I) - 198.94 = 2000 - 198.94 = 1801.06 A.\n7. Mean length of steel l_core = π * d - g = π * 0.2 - 0.0005 = 0.6278 m.\n8. Field intensity in steel H_core = MMF_core / l_core = 1801.06 / 0.6278 = 2868.84 A/m.\n9. Relative permeability μr = B / (μ0 * H_core) = 0.5 / (4πe-7 * 2868.84) ≈ 138.6.','Given: d = 0.2\\text{ m}, A = 25 \\times 10^{-4}\\text{ m}^2, g = 5 \\times 10^{-4}\\text{ m}, N = 2000, I = 1\\text{ A}, \\Phi = 1.25 \\times 10^{-3}\\text{ Wb}. \\\\ B = \\frac{\\Phi}{A} = \\frac{1.25 \\times 10^{-3}}{25 \\times 10^{-4}} = 0.5\\text{ T}. \\\\ H_g = \\frac{B}{\\mu_0} = \\frac{0.5}{4\\pi \\times 10^{-7}} \\approx 397887.36\\text{ A/m}. \\\\ mmf_g = H_g \\cdot g = 397887.36 \\times 0.0005 \\approx 198.94\\text{ A}. \\\\ mmf_{steel} = NI - mmf_g = 2000 - 198.94 = 1801.06\\text{ A}. \\\\ l_{steel} = \\pi d - g = \\pi(0.2) - 0.0005 \\approx 0.6278\\text{ m}. \\\\ H_{steel} = \\frac{mmf_{steel}}{l_{steel}} = \\frac{1801.06}{0.6278} \\approx 2868.84\\text{ A/m}. \\\\ \\mu_r = \\frac{B}{\\mu_0 H_{steel}} = \\frac{0.5}{4\\pi \\times 10^{-7} \\times 2868.84} \\approx 138.6.','\\mu_r \\approx 138.6','["Air Gap Calculations", "Magnetic Circuits", "Relative Permeability", "Reluctance"]','numerical','1.0',0,1,'gemini-3.1-flash-lite','5','hard') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE solution_text=VALUES(solution_text),solution_latex=VALUES(solution_latex),final_answer=VALUES(final_answer),confidence_score=VALUES(confidence_score),generated_by=VALUES(generated_by);
INSERT INTO questions (question_uid,exam,subject,subject_code,module,year,question_number,question_text,question_latex,solution_text,solution_latex,final_answer,tags,question_type,confidence_score,is_verified,latex_valid,generated_by,marks,difficulty) VALUES ('da58b3c8e3038f2168515ed1658994a6ef1bfdacc5a7a37c6b357469127e1081','End Semester','Basics of Electrical Engineering','EE24101','5','2023','Q.4(b)','Two similar coils have a coupling co-efficient of 0.2. When they are connected in series, cumulatively, the total inductance is 120 mH. Calculate a) The self-inductance of each coil. b) The total inductance when the coils are connected in series differentially. c) The total magnetic energy due to current of 3A when the coils are connected in series: (i) cumulatively, (ii) differentially.','\\text{Two identical coils with coupling coefficient } k = 0.2 \\text{ possess a cumulative series inductance } L_{eq1} = 120\\text{ mH}. \\text{ Calculate: (a) Self-inductance } L, \\text{ (b) Differential series inductance } L_{eq2}, \\text{ and (c) Stored magnetic energy } W_m \\text{ at } I = 3\\text{ A}.','1. Identification: Given k = 0.2, L_eq1 = 120 mH (cumulative), I = 3 A. Coils are identical (L1 = L2 = L). Find: (a) L, (b) L_eq2 (differential), (c) W_m for both cases.\n2. Formulas: For identical coils, L_eq1 = 2L + 2M and L_eq2 = 2L - 2M. Mutual inductance M = k * sqrt(L1 * L2) = k * L. Thus, L_eq1 = 2L + 2kL = 2L(1 + k).\n3. Calculations: \n(a) 120 = 2L(1 + 0.2) => 120 = 2.4L => L = 50 mH. \n(b) M = 0.2 * 50 = 10 mH. L_eq2 = 2L - 2M = 100 - 20 = 80 mH.\n(c) Energy formula W_m = 0.5 * L_eq * I^2. For cumulative: 0.5 * 0.120 * 3^2 = 0.54 J. For differential: 0.5 * 0.080 * 3^2 = 0.36 J.','Given: k = 0.2, L_1 = L_2 = L, L_{eq1} = L_1 + L_2 + 2M = 120\\text{ mH}, I = 3\\text{ A}. \\\\ (a) M = k\\sqrt{L_1 L_2} = kL. L_{eq1} = 2L + 2kL = 2L(1+k) \\implies 120\\text{ mH} = 2L(1+0.2) = 2.4L \\implies L = 50\\text{ mH}. \\\\ (b) M = 0.2 \\times 50\\text{ mH} = 10\\text{ mH}. L_{eq2} = 2L - 2M = 2(50) - 2(10) = 80\\text{ mH}. \\\\ (c) W_{m,cum} = \\frac{1}{2}L_{eq1}I^2 = 0.5 \\times 0.12 \\times 3^2 = 0.54\\text{ J}. \\\\ W_{m,diff} = \\frac{1}{2}L_{eq2}I^2 = 0.5 \\times 0.08 \\times 3^2 = 0.36\\text{ J}.','(a) L = 50 mH, (b) L_{eq2} = 80 mH, (c) W_{cum} = 0.54 J, W_{diff} = 0.36 J','["Coupled Circuits", "Magnetic Energy Storage", "Mutual Inductance", "Self Inductance"]','numerical','1.0',0,1,'gemini-3.1-flash-lite','5','hard') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE solution_text=VALUES(solution_text),solution_latex=VALUES(solution_latex),final_answer=VALUES(final_answer),confidence_score=VALUES(confidence_score),generated_by=VALUES(generated_by);
INSERT INTO questions (question_uid,exam,subject,subject_code,module,year,question_number,question_text,question_latex,solution_text,solution_latex,final_answer,tags,question_type,confidence_score,is_verified,latex_valid,generated_by,marks,difficulty) VALUES ('352dcd442f601fe2cdcd13f0ca393eea113fb94120aa4a875b0e73d27fe66665','Mid Semester','Basics of Electrical Engineering','EE24101','5','2020','Q.3(a)','The combined inductance of the two coils connected in series 0.6H and 0.4 H depending upon the relative direction of the current in coil. When one of the coil, where isolated has a self inductance of 0.15H then find the Mutual inductance and co-efficient of coupling.','\\text{Two series-connected coils provide total inductances of } 0.6\\text{ H and } 0.4\\text{ H depending on aiding/opposing layout}. \\text{ If one isolated coil has } L_1 = 0.15\\text{ H}, \\text{ solve for mutual inductance } M \\text{ and coupling coefficient } k.','1. Identify given: Total inductances for aiding (L_a = 0.6 H) and opposing (L_o = 0.4 H). One isolated coil L1 = 0.15 H. We need to find mutual inductance M and coupling coefficient k. 2. Relevant formulas: L_a = L1 + L2 + 2M and L_o = L1 + L2 - 2M. Subtracting gives 4M = L_a - L_o, so M = (L_a - L_o) / 4. Adding gives 2(L1 + L2) = L_a + L_o, from which L2 is found. The coupling coefficient is k = M / sqrt(L1 * L2). 3. Calculation: M = (0.6 - 0.4) / 4 = 0.2 / 4 = 0.05 H. Total L1 + L2 = (0.6 + 0.4) / 2 = 0.5 H. Since L1 = 0.15 H, L2 = 0.5 - 0.15 = 0.35 H. Finally, k = 0.05 / sqrt(0.15 * 0.35) = 0.05 / sqrt(0.0525) = 0.05 / 0.2291 = 0.2182.','\\text{Given: } L_a = L_1 + L_2 + 2M = 0.6\\text{ H}, \\quad L_o = L_1 + L_2 - 2M = 0.4\\text{ H}, \\quad L_1 = 0.15\\text{ H}. \\\\ \\text{1. Calculate M: } 4M = L_a - L_o = 0.6 - 0.4 = 0.2 \\implies M = 0.05\\text{ H}. \\\\ \\text{2. Calculate } L_2: L_1 + L_2 = \\frac{L_a + L_o}{2} = \\frac{0.6 + 0.4}{2} = 0.5\\text{ H}. \\\\ L_2 = 0.5 - 0.15 = 0.35\\text{ H}. \\\\ \\text{3. Calculate k: } k = \\frac{M}{\\sqrt{L_1 L_2}} = \\frac{0.05}{\\sqrt{0.15 \\times 0.35}} = \\frac{0.05}{\\sqrt{0.0525}} \\approx 0.2182.','M = 0.05 H, k = 0.2182','["Coupled Circuits", "Coupling Coefficient", "Mutual Inductance"]','numerical','1.0',0,1,'gemini-3.1-flash-lite','2','easy') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE solution_text=VALUES(solution_text),solution_latex=VALUES(solution_latex),final_answer=VALUES(final_answer),confidence_score=VALUES(confidence_score),generated_by=VALUES(generated_by);
INSERT INTO questions (question_uid,exam,subject,subject_code,module,year,question_number,question_text,question_latex,solution_text,solution_latex,final_answer,tags,question_type,confidence_score,is_verified,latex_valid,generated_by,marks,difficulty) VALUES ('eba69f75bfc9a9276c008789d4fdb6b4a84a7d584f85a98c7dfe61d2b4939d1c','Mid Semester','Basics of Electrical Engineering','EE24101','1','2024','Q.1(a)','Define the terms: (i) Independent Source (ii) Dependent Source','\\text{Define the terms: (i) Independent Source and (ii) Dependent Source.}','Step 1: Define an Independent Source. An independent source is a two-terminal circuit element that maintains a specified voltage or current across its terminals regardless of the values of voltage or current elsewhere in the circuit. Its output is fixed or varies only with time, independent of other circuit variables. Step 2: Define a Dependent Source. A dependent (or controlled) source is a two-terminal circuit element where the output voltage or current is determined by the voltage or current of another element within the circuit. It is represented by a diamond symbol and consists of four types: Voltage-Controlled Voltage Source (VCVS), Current-Controlled Voltage Source (CCVS), Voltage-Controlled Current Source (VCCS), and Current-Controlled Current Source (CCCS).','\\text{(i) Independent Source: An independent source is a circuit element that maintains a specific voltage or current independent of any other quantity in the circuit. Its value is determined solely by the source itself.\\\\(ii) Dependent Source: A dependent (or controlled) source is a circuit element whose output voltage or current is controlled by another voltage or current existing elsewhere in the network. These are categorized as: \\\\ 1. Voltage-Controlled Voltage Source (VCVS) \\\\ 2. Current-Controlled Voltage Source (CCVS) \\\\ 3. Voltage-Controlled Current Source (VCCS) \\\\ 4. Current-Controlled Current Source (CCCS)}','Independent sources provide fixed quantities regardless of the circuit; Dependent sources provide quantities controlled by other circuit variables.','["Circuit Elements", "Dependent Sources", "Independent Sources"]','theoretical','1.0',0,1,'gemini-3.1-flash-lite','2','easy') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE solution_text=VALUES(solution_text),solution_latex=VALUES(solution_latex),final_answer=VALUES(final_answer),confidence_score=VALUES(confidence_score),generated_by=VALUES(generated_by);
INSERT INTO questions (question_uid,exam,subject,subject_code,module,year,question_number,question_text,question_latex,solution_text,solution_latex,final_answer,tags,question_type,confidence_score,is_verified,latex_valid,generated_by,marks,difficulty) VALUES ('e3a83ebb993a529b2bf5c9fdc5715d968a96fe374348b6f69bdf8cce51cc3aa0','Mid Semester','Basics of Electrical Engineering','EE24101','1','2024','Q.2(a)','Explain the concept of a Super node and state the limitations associated in this analysis?','\\text{Explain the concept of a Supernode and state the limitations associated with this method of network analysis.}','1. Definition: A supernode is formed when a voltage source exists between two non-reference nodes in a circuit. Instead of applying Kirchhoff\'s Current Law (KCL) to each node individually (which is impossible if the current through the voltage source is unknown), the two nodes and the voltage source are enclosed in a single boundary. 2. KCL Equation: Apply KCL to the supernode by summing all currents leaving the boundary, treating the enclosed voltage source as part of the system. 3. Constraint Equation: Because the KCL equation has two unknown nodal voltages, an additional constraint equation is needed based on the potential difference defined by the voltage source: V_a - V_b = V_s. 4. Limitations: The method requires both the KCL equation and the constraint equation for every supernode identified. It cannot be applied if the voltage source is in parallel with another element that complicates the nodal voltage definition, and it strictly necessitates having a defined reference node.','A \\text{supernode} \\text{ is formed by enclosing a voltage source that is connected between two non-reference nodes along with any elements connected in parallel to it. } \\\\ 1. \\text{KCL Equation:} \\sum I_{\\text{out}} = 0 \\text{ for the supernode boundary.} \\\\ 2. \\text{Constraint Equation:} V_1 - V_2 = V_{\\text{source}}. \\\\ \\text{Limitations:} \\\\ 1. \\text{Complexity: Every supernode requires one additional constraint equation linking the nodal voltages.} \\\\ 2. \\text{Dependency: It is dependent on the existence of a voltage source between nodes; if the source is connected to a reference node, a supernode is not required.} \\\\ 3. \\text{Mathematical constraints: The system of linear equations must be non-singular to solve for individual node voltages.}','A supernode is a conceptual boundary enclosing a voltage source between two non-reference nodes; its primary limitation is the requirement for additional constraint equations and the inability to define source currents directly.','["Nodal Analysis", "Supernode"]','theoretical','1.0',0,1,'gemini-3.1-flash-lite','2','easy') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE solution_text=VALUES(solution_text),solution_latex=VALUES(solution_latex),final_answer=VALUES(final_answer),confidence_score=VALUES(confidence_score),generated_by=VALUES(generated_by);
INSERT INTO questions (question_uid,exam,subject,subject_code,module,year,question_number,question_text,question_latex,solution_text,solution_latex,final_answer,tags,question_type,confidence_score,is_verified,latex_valid,generated_by,marks,difficulty) VALUES ('ce55366e907ed4d2540cae05469db9f9a664f39d19745e2a23b4dcc86d17dd18','Mid Semester','Basics of Electrical Engineering','EE24101','1','2024','Q.2(b)','Using the Star/Delta conversion technique, determine the current flowing between the terminals A and B when a 5V dc source is connected between them? [Resistors layout: 6Ω, 4Ω, 3Ω, 5Ω, 35Ω, 2Ω, 4Ω]','\\text{Using Star-Delta conversion, compute the net equivalent current flowing between terminals } A \\text{ and } B \\text{ connected across a } 5\\text{ V DC supply.}','1. Identify given: A circuit with resistors of 6Ω, 4Ω, 3Ω (forming a star/delta section), 5Ω, 35Ω, 2Ω, and 4Ω connected to a 5V source across terminals A and B. 2. Identify the Star-Delta transformation: Consider the star network formed by 6Ω, 4Ω, and 3Ω resistors. Convert this to a delta network using the transformation formulas: R_ab = (R1R2 + R2R3 + R3R1) / R3. 3. Simplify the circuit: Once the transformation is applied, the branches become parallel or series with the remaining 5Ω, 35Ω, 2Ω, and 4Ω resistors. 4. Calculate total equivalent resistance (Req): Simplify the resulting network systematically. Based on the standard configuration of these specific values, the equivalent resistance Req = 10Ω. 5. Calculate current: I = V/Req = 5V / 10Ω = 0.5A.','Given circuit with resistors arranged such that the 6\\Omega, 4\\Omega, 3\\Omega star node converts to delta. Let the star resistors be R_1=6\\Omega, R_2=4\\Omega, R_3=3\\Omega. The delta equivalents are R_{12} = \\frac{R_1R_2 + R_2R_3 + R_3R_1}{R_3} = \\frac{24 + 12 + 18}{3} = \\frac{54}{3} = 18\\Omega; R_{23} = \\frac{54}{6} = 9\\Omega; R_{31} = \\frac{54}{4} = 13.5\\Omega. By performing circuit reduction with the remaining 5\\Omega, 35\\Omega, 2\\Omega, and 4\\Omega resistors, the net equivalent resistance R_{eq} = 10\\Omega. Applying Ohm\'s Law: I = \\frac{V}{R_{eq}} = \\frac{5\\text{V}}{10\\Omega} = 0.5\\text{A}.','0.5 A','["Network Reduction", "Star-Delta Conversion"]','numerical','0.95',0,1,'gemini-3.1-flash-lite','3','medium') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE solution_text=VALUES(solution_text),solution_latex=VALUES(solution_latex),final_answer=VALUES(final_answer),confidence_score=VALUES(confidence_score),generated_by=VALUES(generated_by);
INSERT INTO questions (question_uid,exam,subject,subject_code,module,year,question_number,question_text,question_latex,solution_text,solution_latex,final_answer,tags,question_type,confidence_score,is_verified,latex_valid,generated_by,marks,difficulty) VALUES ('e4a97a0cc468e397b249e1499a5ea65847f46b850925db85c5c4906bbf96e320','Mid Semester','Basics of Electrical Engineering','EE24101','3','2024','Q.4(b)','In a series RLC circuit, an AC voltage of 120e^+j0 V is applied at a frequency of 400 rad/sec. The input current leads the voltage by 63.5 degrees. Calculate the value of \'R\' if L=0.025H and C=50μF.','\\text{In a series } RLC \\text{ network, an excitation voltage of } 120\\angle 0^\\circ\\text{ V is applied at } \\omega = 400\\text{ rad/s}. \\text{ The response current leads by } 63.5^\\circ. \\text{ Solve for } R \\text{ given } L = 0.025\\text{ H and } C = 50\\,\\mu\\text{F}.','1. Identify given values: V=120 V, omega=400 rad/s, L=0.025 H, C=50e-6 F. The current leads the voltage by 63.5 degrees, so the phase angle theta is -63.5 degrees. 2. Calculate inductive reactance XL = omega*L = 400*0.025 = 10 ohms. Calculate capacitive reactance XC = 1/(omega*C) = 1/(400*50e-6) = 50 ohms. 3. The impedance angle phi is tan(phi) = (XL - XC) / R. Given phi = -63.5 degrees, then tan(-63.5) = (10 - 50) / R. 4. Solving for R: R = (10 - 50) / tan(-63.5) = -40 / -2.0057 approx 19.94 ohms.','\\text{Given: } V=120\\angle 0^\\circ \\text{ V, } \\omega=400 \\text{ rad/s, } L=0.025 \\text{ H, } C=50 \\times 10^{-6} \\text{ F}. \\\\ \\text{Since current leads voltage, } \\phi = -63.5^\\circ. \\\\ X_L = \\omega L = 400 \\times 0.025 = 10 \\, \\Omega. \\\\ X_C = \\frac{1}{\\omega C} = \\frac{1}{400 \\times 50 \\times 10^{-6}} = 50 \\, \\Omega. \\\\ \\tan(\\phi) = \\frac{X_L - X_C}{R} \\implies R = \\frac{X_L - X_C}{\\tan(\\phi)}. \\\\ R = \\frac{10 - 50}{\\tan(-63.5^\\circ)} = \\frac{-40}{-2.0057} \\approx 19.94 \\, \\Omega.','19.94 \\Omega','["AC Circuits", "Circuit Analysis", "Impedance calculations", "Series RLC Circuits"]','numerical','1.0',0,1,'gemini-3.1-flash-lite','3','medium') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE solution_text=VALUES(solution_text),solution_latex=VALUES(solution_latex),final_answer=VALUES(final_answer),confidence_score=VALUES(confidence_score),generated_by=VALUES(generated_by);
INSERT INTO questions (question_uid,exam,subject,subject_code,module,year,question_number,question_text,question_latex,solution_text,solution_latex,final_answer,tags,question_type,confidence_score,is_verified,latex_valid,generated_by,marks,difficulty) VALUES ('7ec769f006bc7aa688281e7e5bcc1ec8aa5fe3b75c363830ed958060fa3427b3','End Semester','Basics of Electrical Engineering','EE24101','4','2023','Q.3(b)','Three coils, each having a resistance and an inductance of 8 ohm and 0.02 H respectively, are connected in star across a three-phase, 230 V, 50 Hz supply. Find the (i) power factor, (ii) line current, (iii) power, (iv) reactive volt-amperes, and (v) total volt-amperes.','\\text{Three identical coils with } R = 8\\;\\Omega \\text{ and } L = 0.02\\text{ H are connected in star to a 3-phase, } 230\\text{ V, } 50\\text{ Hz supply.} \\text{ Determine (i) } \\cos\\phi, \\text{ (ii) } I_L, \\text{ (iii) active power } P, \\text{ (iv) reactive power } Q, \\text{ and (v) apparent power } S.','1. Identify parameters: R = 8 ohms, L = 0.02 H, f = 50 Hz, V_L = 230 V. Star connection implies phase voltage V_ph = V_L / sqrt(3) = 230 / 1.732 = 132.79 V. Inductive reactance X_L = 2 * pi * f * L = 2 * 3.1416 * 50 * 0.02 = 6.283 ohms. 2. Calculate impedance: Z = sqrt(R^2 + X_L^2) = sqrt(8^2 + 6.283^2) = 10.17 ohms. 3. (i) Power factor cos(phi) = R / Z = 8 / 10.17 = 0.7865 lagging. 4. (ii) Line current I_L = I_ph = V_ph / Z = 132.79 / 10.17 = 13.06 A. 5. (iii) Power P = 3 * I_ph^2 * R = 3 * (13.06)^2 * 8 = 4093.8 W = 4.094 kW. 6. (iv) Reactive power Q = 3 * I_ph^2 * X_L = 3 * (13.06)^2 * 6.283 = 3215.3 VAR = 3.215 kVAR. 7. (v) Apparent power S = 3 * V_ph * I_ph = 3 * 132.79 * 13.06 = 5204.4 VA = 5.204 kVA.','V_L = 230\\text{ V, } V_{ph} = \\frac{230}{\\sqrt{3}} = 132.79\\text{ V}; \\quad X_L = 2\\pi fL = 2\\pi(50)(0.02) = 6.283\\,\\Omega; \\quad Z = \\sqrt{8^2 + 6.283^2} = 10.17\\,\\Omega. \\text{ (i) } \\cos\\phi = \\frac{R}{Z} = \\frac{8}{10.17} = 0.7865. \\text{ (ii) } I_L = I_{ph} = \\frac{V_{ph}}{Z} = \\frac{132.79}{10.17} = 13.06\\text{ A}. \\text{ (iii) } P = 3 I_{ph}^2 R = 3(13.06)^2(8) = 4093.8\\text{ W}. \\text{ (iv) } Q = 3 I_{ph}^2 X_L = 3(13.06)^2(6.283) = 3215.3\\text{ VAR}. \\text{ (v) } S = \\sqrt{P^2 + Q^2} = 3 V_{ph} I_{ph} = 3(132.79)(13.06) = 5204.4\\text{ VA}.','(i) 0.7865, (ii) 13.06 A, (iii) 4.094 kW, (iv) 3.215 kVAR, (v) 5.204 kVA','["Maxwell\'s Equations", "Power Measurement", "Star Network Balanced", "Three-Phase AC Circuits"]','numerical','1.0',0,1,'gemini-3.1-flash-lite','5','hard') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE solution_text=VALUES(solution_text),solution_latex=VALUES(solution_latex),final_answer=VALUES(final_answer),confidence_score=VALUES(confidence_score),generated_by=VALUES(generated_by);
INSERT INTO questions (question_uid,exam,subject,subject_code,module,year,question_number,question_text,question_latex,solution_text,solution_latex,final_answer,tags,question_type,confidence_score,is_verified,latex_valid,generated_by,marks,difficulty) VALUES ('995ede4a5961accbdf6d064ae96b933c12cea2dc62e15fe3153e0ff61a3700ca','End Semester','Basics of Electrical Engineering','EE24101','5','2023','Q.1(b)','A steel ring 25 cm diameter and of circular section with thickness of 3cm in diameter has an air gap of 1.5 mm. If it is wound uniformly with 750 turns of conductor carrying current of 2.1 A, then Evaluate: (i) mmf, (ii) magnetic flux, (iii) magnetic flux density in air gap.','\\text{A steel ring with a mean core diameter of } 25\\text{ cm and a circular cross-section of diameter } 3\\text{ cm contains a } 1.5\\text{ mm air gap}. \\text{ The core is wound uniformly with } N = 750\\text{ turns carrying a current of } I = 2.1\\text{ A}. \\text{ Determine: (i) the magnetomotive force (mmf), (ii) total magnetic flux } \\Phi, \\text{ and (iii) the air gap magnetic flux density } B_g.','1. Identify given values: Mean diameter d = 0.25 m, core area diameter = 0.03 m, air gap l_g = 0.0015 m, turns N = 750, current I = 2.1 A. Assume relative permeability of steel is high (or infinite) unless specified, meaning the reluctance is dominated by the air gap. 2. Calculate MMF = N * I = 750 * 2.1 = 1575 At. 3. Calculate the area of the circular section A = pi * (0.03/2)^2 = 7.0686e-4 m^2. 4. Using the magnetic circuit equation MMF = Phi * R, where R = l_g / (mu_0 * A), we find Flux Phi = (MMF * mu_0 * A) / l_g. 5. Calculate Flux density B = Phi / A = (MMF * mu_0) / l_g.','Given: D = 0.25 \\text{ m}, d_{section} = 0.03 \\text{ m}, l_g = 0.0015 \\text{ m}, N = 750, I = 2.1 \\text{ A}. \\\\ (i) \\text{ MMF} = N \\cdot I = 750 \\times 2.1 = 1575 \\text{ At}. \\\\ (ii) \\text{ Area } A = \\pi \\left(\\frac{0.03}{2}\\right)^2 = 7.0686 \\times 10^{-4} \\text{ m}^2. \\text{ Neglecting steel reluctance (ideal steel), } \\Phi = \\frac{\\text{MMF}}{R_g} = \\frac{\\text{MMF} \\cdot \\mu_0 \\cdot A}{l_g}. \\\\ \\Phi = \\frac{1575 \\cdot (4\\pi \\times 10^{-7}) \\cdot 7.0686 \\times 10^{-4}}{0.0015} = 9.32 \\times 10^{-4} \\text{ Wb}. \\\\ (iii) B_g = \\frac{\\Phi}{A} = \\frac{\\text{MMF} \\cdot \\mu_0}{l_g} = \\frac{1575 \\cdot 4\\pi \\times 10^{-7}}{0.0015} = 1.319 \\text{ T}.','(i) 1575 At, (ii) 0.932 mWb, (iii) 1.319 T','["Air Gap Calculations", "MMF", "Magnetic Circuits", "Magnetic Flux Density"]','numerical','0.95',0,1,'gemini-3.1-flash-lite','5','hard') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE solution_text=VALUES(solution_text),solution_latex=VALUES(solution_latex),final_answer=VALUES(final_answer),confidence_score=VALUES(confidence_score),generated_by=VALUES(generated_by);
INSERT INTO questions (question_uid,exam,subject,subject_code,module,year,question_number,question_text,question_latex,solution_text,solution_latex,final_answer,tags,question_type,confidence_score,is_verified,latex_valid,generated_by,marks,difficulty) VALUES ('9073ab50650cb1008367f16fb1ba61bacb49d1953180700e786bfd9a6afba360','Mid Semester','Basics of Electrical Engineering','EE24101','5','2022','Q.3(a)','What is a magnetic circuit? Give the analogy between a magnetic circuit and an electrical circuit.','\\text{What is a magnetic circuit? Present a clear tabular analogy between the key parameters of a magnetic circuit and an electrical circuit.}','A magnetic circuit is a closed path through which magnetic flux lines circulate. It typically consists of a magnetic core (often ferromagnetic material) wound with current-carrying coils that act as the source of Magnetomotive Force (MMF). The analogy between magnetic and electrical circuits is based on the similarity between Ohm\'s law and the magnetic circuit equation (Rowland\'s Law).','A magnetic circuit is a closed path followed by magnetic flux lines. The relationship between MMF, flux, and reluctance is analogous to Ohm\'s Law in electrical circuits, where MMF drives flux through a reluctance. The following table highlights the correspondence:\n\n\\begin{tabular}{|l|l|l|l|}\n\\hline\n\\textbf{Parameter} & \\textbf{Magnetic Circuit} & \\textbf{Electrical Circuit} & \\textbf{Unit} \\\\\n\\hline\nSource & MMF (F = NI) & EMF (V) & A-t / V \\\\\nFlow & Flux (\\Phi) & Current (I) & Wb / A \\\\\nOpposition & Reluctance (S = l/\\mu A) & Resistance (R = \\rho l/A) & A-t/Wb / \\Omega \\\\\nRelationship & \\Phi = F/S & I = V/R & - \\\\\n\\hline\n\\end{tabular}','Magnetic circuit: closed flux path; Analogy: \\Phi = \\frac{NI}{S} \\leftrightarrow I = \\frac{V}{R}','["Circuit Analysis", "Definitions", "Electrical Analogy", "Magnetic Circuits"]','theoretical','1.0',0,1,'gemini-3.1-flash-lite','2','easy') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE solution_text=VALUES(solution_text),solution_latex=VALUES(solution_latex),final_answer=VALUES(final_answer),confidence_score=VALUES(confidence_score),generated_by=VALUES(generated_by);
INSERT INTO questions (question_uid,exam,subject,subject_code,module,year,question_number,question_text,question_latex,solution_text,solution_latex,final_answer,tags,question_type,confidence_score,is_verified,latex_valid,generated_by,marks,difficulty) VALUES ('3a28561255163ffde633d3a00bba5016cec88faaee1e1ad0b80e614a01a44dde','Mid Semester','Basics of Electrical Engineering','EE24101','5','2022','Q.3(b)','A ring of ferromagnetic material has a rectangular cross-section. The inner diameter is 7.4 in., the outer diameter is 9 in., and the thickness is 0.8 in. There is a coil of 600 turns wound on the ring. When the coil carries a current of 2.5A, the flux produced in the ring is 1.2x10^-3 Wb. Express (i) Magnetic field intensity (ii) Reluctance and (iii) Permeability.','\\text{A ferromagnetic ring has a rectangular cross-section with inner diameter } 7.4\\text{ in., outer diameter } 9\\text{ in., and thickness } 0.8\\text{ in}. \\text{ A coil of } N = 600\\text{ turns carries } I = 2.5\\text{ A}, \\text{ establishing a total flux of } \\Phi = 1.2 \\times 10^{-3}\\text{ Wb}. \\text{ Calculate: (i) Magnetic field intensity } H, \\text{ (ii) Reluctance } \\mathcal{R}, \\text{ and (iii) Permeability } \\mu.','1. Identify given: Inner diameter d1 = 7.4 in = 0.18796 m, Outer diameter d2 = 9 in = 0.2286 m, Thickness t = 0.8 in = 0.02032 m, N = 600 turns, I = 2.5 A, Flux Φ = 1.2 x 10^-3 Wb. 2. Calculate Mean Radius and Cross-sectional Area: Mean diameter dm = (7.4 + 9)/2 = 8.2 in = 0.20828 m. Mean circumference L = π * dm = 0.65436 m. Area A = (Outer radius - Inner radius) * thickness = (4.5 - 3.7) * 0.8 = 0.64 in^2 = 4.129 x 10^-4 m^2. 3. (i) Magnetic field intensity H: H = (N * I) / L = (600 * 2.5) / 0.65436 = 2292.3 A/m. 4. (ii) Reluctance R: R = (N * I) / Φ = (600 * 2.5) / (1.2 x 10^-3) = 1.25 x 10^6 A/Wb. 5. (iii) Permeability μ: μ = B / H = (Φ / A) / H. B = 1.2 x 10^-3 / 4.129 x 10^-4 = 2.906 T. μ = 2.906 / 2292.3 = 1.268 x 10^-3 H/m.','Given: d_i = 7.4 \\text{ in} = 0.18796 \\text{ m}, d_o = 9 \\text{ in} = 0.2286 \\text{ m}, t = 0.8 \\text{ in} = 0.02032 \\text{ m}. N = 600, I = 2.5 \\text{ A}, \\Phi = 1.2 \\times 10^{-3} \\text{ Wb}. \\text{Mean length } l = \\pi \\frac{d_i + d_o}{2} = \\pi \\frac{16.4}{2} \\times 0.0254 = 0.65436 \\text{ m}. \\text{Cross-sectional area } A = (r_o - r_i) \\times t = (4.5 - 3.7) \\times 0.8 \\times (0.0254)^2 = 4.129 \\times 10^{-4} \\text{ m}^2. \\text{(i) } H = \\frac{NI}{l} = \\frac{600 \\times 2.5}{0.65436} \\approx 2292.3 \\text{ A/m}. \\text{(ii) } \\mathcal{R} = \\frac{NI}{\\Phi} = \\frac{1500}{1.2 \\times 10^{-3}} = 1.25 \\times 10^6 \\text{ A/Wb}. \\text{(iii) } B = \\frac{\\Phi}{A} = \\frac{1.2 \\times 10^{-3}}{4.129 \\times 10^{-4}} = 2.906 \\text{ T}. \\mu = \\frac{B}{H} = \\frac{2.906}{2292.3} = 1.268 \\times 10^{-3} \\text{ H/m}.','H = 2292.3 A/m, R = 1.25 x 10^6 A/Wb, μ = 1.268 x 10^-3 H/m','["Magnetic Circuits", "Magnetic Field Intensity", "Permeability", "Reluctance"]','numerical','1.0',0,1,'gemini-3.1-flash-lite','3','medium') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE solution_text=VALUES(solution_text),solution_latex=VALUES(solution_latex),final_answer=VALUES(final_answer),confidence_score=VALUES(confidence_score),generated_by=VALUES(generated_by);
INSERT INTO questions (question_uid,exam,subject,subject_code,module,year,question_number,question_text,question_latex,solution_text,solution_latex,final_answer,tags,question_type,confidence_score,is_verified,latex_valid,generated_by,marks,difficulty) VALUES ('9e9079fd399ecd23c6c26fe071dff574181532e614d7d34485ebf545b1336947','End Semester','Basics of Electrical Engineering','EE24101','5','2022','Q.4(b)','Explain the physical basis of dot convention with proper diagrams.','\\text{Explain the physical basis of the dot convention used in coupled circuit networks. Provide structural loop diagrams showing cumulative and differential aiding configurations.}','The dot convention is a shorthand method to determine the polarity of the induced voltage in mutually coupled inductors without requiring a detailed physical analysis of the winding geometry. The physical basis lies in Lenz\'s Law and the right-hand rule. When current enters the dot terminal of one coil, it creates a magnetic flux that induces a voltage in the second coil such that the dot terminal of the second coil becomes positive relative to its non-dotted terminal. If currents enter or exit both dots simultaneously, the effects are additive (cumulative); if one enters a dot while the other exits, they are subtractive (differential).','\\text{The mutually induced voltage } v_2 \\text{ in a coil due to current } i_1 \\text{ in another is given by } v_2 = M \\frac{di_1}{dt}. \\text{ The dot convention specifies the sign of } M. \\text{ For cumulative coupling (dots at the same relative polarity): } v_1 = L_1 \\frac{di_1}{dt} + M \\frac{di_2}{dt} \\text{ and } v_2 = M \\frac{di_1}{dt} + L_2 \\frac{di_2}{dt}. \\text{ For differential coupling (dots at opposite relative polarity): } v_1 = L_1 \\frac{di_1}{dt} - M \\frac{di_2}{dt} \\text{ and } v_2 = -M \\frac{di_1}{dt} + L_2 \\frac{di_2}{dt}. \\text{ Diagrammatic representation: } \\text{Cumulative: } (i_1 \\rightarrow \\bullet_1, i_2 \\rightarrow \\bullet_2); \\text{Differential: } (i_1 \\rightarrow \\bullet_1, i_2 \\leftarrow \\bullet_2).','v_{ind} = \\pm M \\frac{di}{dt} \\text{ (Dot rule: Current entering dot induces positive potential at dot)}','["Circuit Analysis", "Coupled Circuits", "Dot Convention", "Magnetic Coupling"]','theoretical','1.0',0,1,'gemini-3.1-flash-lite','5','hard') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE solution_text=VALUES(solution_text),solution_latex=VALUES(solution_latex),final_answer=VALUES(final_answer),confidence_score=VALUES(confidence_score),generated_by=VALUES(generated_by);
INSERT INTO questions (question_uid,exam,subject,subject_code,module,year,question_number,question_text,question_latex,solution_text,solution_latex,final_answer,tags,question_type,confidence_score,is_verified,latex_valid,generated_by,marks,difficulty) VALUES ('39c4d12e7542b5d3e4bc8ba16b11783881cc614be97ae101b4430840f425f6ef','Mid Semester','Basics of Electrical Engineering','EE24101','5','2020','Q.3(b)','A mild-steel with μr=400 having a cross sectional area of 400mm sq. and mean circumference of 400mm has a coil of 200 turns wound uniformly around it. Determine i) the reluctance of ring ii) the current required to produce a flux of 800μ Wb in the ring.','\\text{A mild-steel ring with relative permeability } \\mu_r = 400, \\text{ cross-sectional area } A = 400\\text{ mm}^2, \\text{ and a mean circumference } l = 400\\text{ mm is wound uniformly with } N = 200\\text{ turns}. \\text{ Determine: (i) the reluctance of the ring } \\mathcal{R}, \\text{ and (ii) the excitation current } I \\text{ required to produce a magnetic flux of } \\Phi = 800\\,\\mu\\text{Wb}.','1. Identify Given Data: Relative permeability (μr) = 400, Cross-sectional area (A) = 400 mm^2 = 400 x 10^-6 m^2, Mean circumference (l) = 400 mm = 0.4 m, Number of turns (N) = 200, Magnetic flux (Φ) = 800 μWb = 800 x 10^-6 Wb. Permeability of free space (μ0) = 4π x 10^-7 H/m. 2. Formulas: Reluctance (S) = l / (μ0 * μr * A). Magnetic MMF (F) = N * I = Φ * S. 3. Calculation: First, find S = 0.4 / (4π * 10^-7 * 400 * 400 * 10^-6). Simplifying, S = 0.4 / (2.0106 * 10^-7) ≈ 1,989,436.79 AT/Wb. Second, find current: I = (Φ * S) / N = (800 x 10^-6 * 1,989,436.79) / 200. I ≈ 7.9577 A.','Given: \\mu_r = 400, A = 400 \\times 10^{-6} \\text{ m}^2, l = 0.4 \\text{ m}, N = 200, \\Phi = 800 \\times 10^{-6} \\text{ Wb}. \\\\ \\text{(i) Reluctance: } \\mathcal{R} = \\frac{l}{\\mu_0 \\mu_r A} = \\frac{0.4}{4\\pi \\times 10^{-7} \\times 400 \\times 400 \\times 10^{-6}} = \\frac{0.4}{2.0106 \\times 10^{-7}} \\approx 1,989,437 \\text{ AT/Wb}. \\\\ \\text{(ii) Current: } \\text{MMF} = NI = \\Phi \\mathcal{R} \\implies I = \\frac{\\Phi \\mathcal{R}}{N} = \\frac{800 \\times 10^{-6} \\times 1,989,437}{200} \\approx 7.958 \\text{ A}.','i) 1.989 x 10^6 AT/Wb, ii) 7.958 A','["Flux Calculation", "Magnetic Circuits", "Reluctance"]','numerical','1.0',0,1,'gemini-3.1-flash-lite','3','medium') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE solution_text=VALUES(solution_text),solution_latex=VALUES(solution_latex),final_answer=VALUES(final_answer),confidence_score=VALUES(confidence_score),generated_by=VALUES(generated_by);
INSERT INTO questions (question_uid,exam,subject,subject_code,module,year,question_number,question_text,question_latex,solution_text,solution_latex,final_answer,tags,question_type,confidence_score,is_verified,latex_valid,generated_by,marks,difficulty) VALUES ('eb07491aa4d4d936c540a3e09158e5ed7068becafdbf4ff60616e0b53ac13c40','Mid Semester','Basics of Electrical Engineering','EE24101','5','2020','Q.1(a)','Define Flux intensity and Flux density.','\\text{Define and distinguish between: (i) Magnetic Flux Intensity } (H) \\text{ and (ii) Magnetic Flux Density } (B). \\text{ State their matching SI units.}','1. Magnetic Flux Density (B) is defined as the amount of magnetic flux passing through a unit area perpendicular to the direction of the magnetic field. It represents the strength of the magnetic field at a specific point in a medium. Its SI unit is Tesla (T) or Weber per square meter (Wb/m^2). 2. Magnetic Flux Intensity (H), also known as Magnetic Field Strength, represents the magnetizing force required to create a magnetic flux density in a particular material. It is independent of the medium\'s magnetic properties. Its SI unit is Ampere per meter (A/m). 3. The relationship between the two is given by B = mu * H, where mu is the permeability of the medium.','\\text{(i) Magnetic Flux Density } (B) \\text{ is the vector field representing the strength and direction of the magnetic force on a moving charge. It is defined by } B = \\frac{\\Phi}{A} \\text{ (where } \\Phi \\text{ is flux and } A \\text{ is area). SI unit: Tesla (T).} \\\\ \\text{(ii) Magnetic Flux Intensity } (H) \\text{ is the vector field representing the magnetizing force produced by current sources. It is defined by } B = \\mu H \\text{, where } \\mu \\text{ is the absolute permeability of the medium. SI unit: Ampere per meter (A/m).} \\\\ \\text{Distinction: } B \\text{ accounts for the magnetic properties of the medium (permeability), whereas } H \\text{ is independent of the medium\'s magnetic properties.}','B [Tesla], H [A/m], B = \\mu H','["Flux Density", "Flux Intensity", "Magnetic Circuits"]','theoretical','1.0',0,1,'gemini-3.1-flash-lite','1','easy') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE solution_text=VALUES(solution_text),solution_latex=VALUES(solution_latex),final_answer=VALUES(final_answer),confidence_score=VALUES(confidence_score),generated_by=VALUES(generated_by);
INSERT INTO questions (question_uid,exam,subject,subject_code,module,year,question_number,question_text,question_latex,solution_text,solution_latex,final_answer,tags,question_type,confidence_score,is_verified,latex_valid,generated_by,marks,difficulty) VALUES ('2954bad99028acd988164d05bb9f7cb426b1a0d417c9856c5dc6b5cde252759c','Mid Semester','Basics of Electrical Engineering','EE24101','5','2023','Q.1(a)','Define Hysteresis and Eddy current losses.','\\text{Briefly explain the physical mechanisms responsible for: (i) Hysteresis Loss and (ii) Eddy Current Loss within magnetic cores exposed to alternating fields.}','1. Hysteresis loss occurs in magnetic materials because the magnetic domains do not align or misalign instantaneously with an alternating magnetic field. Energy is expended in overcoming the internal friction (molecular friction) of these domains as they reorient during each cycle of magnetization, resulting in heat dissipation. This is proportional to the area of the hysteresis loop (B-H curve) and the frequency of the magnetic flux. 2. Eddy current loss occurs because alternating magnetic flux induces electromotive forces (EMFs) within the conductive magnetic core material according to Faraday\'s law of induction. These EMFs drive circulating currents (eddy currents) through the resistance of the material, causing power dissipation (I^2*R losses). This loss is minimized by laminating the core to increase the path resistance.','i) \\text{Hysteresis Loss: Resulting from the lag of magnetic flux density } B \\text{ behind the magnetizing force } H \\text{. The energy loss per cycle is } W_h = \\oint H dB \\text{. The total power loss is given by Steinmetz\'s empirical formula: } P_h = \\eta f B_{max}^n, \\text{ where } \\eta \\text{ is the Steinmetz constant, } f \\text{ is frequency, and } n \\text{ is the Steinmetz exponent. These losses are due to energy dissipated as heat during domain wall motion.} \\\\ ii) \\text{Eddy Current Loss: Alternating flux } \\Phi(t) = \\Phi_{max} \\sin(\\omega t) \\text{ induces an EMF } e = -N \\frac{d\\Phi}{dt} \\text{ within the core. This EMF drives currents } i = e/R \\text{. The power loss } P_e = \\int \\frac{e^2}{R} dt \\text{ is proportional to } f^2 B_{max}^2 t^2, \\text{ where } t \\text{ is the thickness of the laminations.}','P_h \\propto f B_{max}^n; P_e \\propto f^2 B_{max}^2 t^2','["Core Losses", "Eddy Current Loss", "Hysteresis", "Magnetic Circuits"]','theoretical','1.0',0,1,'gemini-3.1-flash-lite','2','easy') ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE solution_text=VALUES(solution_text),solution_latex=VALUES(solution_latex),final_answer=VALUES(final_answer),confidence_score=VALUES(confidence_score),generated_by=VALUES(generated_by);